thoughts.a: The input and output grids are the same size. At first glance, they look extremely similar to each other with just a few tiles of difference. In the input grid, we notice there's a green color background and then four objects that are nearly the same shape, but not quite. They all look like either circles or nearly filled circles, sometimes with an opening in them. The output grid contains objects in the same locations as the objects in the input grid, but they have all been completed in some way. Specifically now all the objects in the output grid are the same exact shape. They are the shape of a single tile layer outline of a plus sign. The hypothesis is the following. The input grid will be some color background, probably green. In the input grid, there will be some number of objects scattered throughout. These objects will be nearly completed versions of single layer outlines of plus signs. However, these objects will be corrupted in some way, usually missing some number of tiles that are needed to complete this single layer outline of the plus sign shape. The output grid will thus be the same as the input grid, but with the exception that you need to add each object's missing tiles to complete each object's single tile layer of the plus sign.
thoughts.b: Input and output grids are, again, the same sizes. In In this case, we have a background color of red and two objects, neither of which are circles with plus sign shapes in the middle of them. Thus our hypothesis is wrong. Or rather, our hypothesis was too specific and it needs to be made more general. The shae that needs to be completed by adding tiles in the correct places in the output grid needs to be learned from the objects in the input grid of that example pair, not across all example pairs. For example, In the previous input-output pair we had four such incomplete objects in the input grid from the combination of all four objects, we could see which parts needed to be added to make them all the same. In this input grid, we have two newly shaped objects, but they are pretty similar shapes to each other. from the overlap of the missing parts, We can make a guess as to where the new tiles need to be added to complete both shapes. Notice that both types of shapes in both pairs of inputs have lots of symmetry to them, both mirror, horizontal, and vertical symmetry, Which should help in determining which exact tiles are missing and thus need to be added in the output grid. In this example pair, the shape is a Tic-Tac-Toe like shape, with two sets of orthogonal intersecting parallel lines. We should carefully inspect the input grids and the shapes within them to make certain that we are clear about what the target object should be.
thoughts.c: The input grid has a yellow color background with three different color objects in it. Each object is slightly different with some missing tiles in each. When we look at all three shapes at the same time we can kind of overlap them to see which tiles would be missing from each. the target shape of the final object for all three colors has horizontal and vertical symmetry, which helps us further to identify exactly which tiles need to be added to complete the shape. Tape in this case is kind of like a bullseye, consisting of four small L-shaped objects placed in a specific orientation and pattern to make the overall object of that color. The rest of the output grid is a copy of the input grid, with the exception of adding these specific tiles that complete the corrupted or incomplete objects. Thus, the hypothesis holds.
thoughts.d: We apply the hypothesis here. We notice a yellow background and three different color incomplete objects. According to the hypothesis, we need to inspect closely at the three separate objects to find the similarities and differences between them. We expect the final target shape for all three of them to have vertical and horizontal symmetries. From inspection, the red object looks the least corrupted and nearly contains horizontal and vertical symmetries already. When overlapping the red with the blue object, the missing tiles of each inform us of the final target shape that needs to be reconstructed in the output grid. Target shaped object is a five by five square with four single-tile holes in it. Thus according to the hypothesis, each of the red, green, and blue objects need to be completed into this 5x5 square with four single-tile holes in it, in the exact location they are in the input grid. The background color stays the same color.
thoughts.e: We apply the hypothesis here. In the input grid we have an aqua color background with four different objects: blue, pink, yellow, and green. According to the hypothesis, we need to look at and closely inspect each of these incomplete or corrupted objects, and compare and contrast them to try to deduce the target shape. The final target shape for each object will very likely have vertical and horizontal symmetries. Blue and yellow objects both look the most complete and nearly have symmetries already. When we inspect these two specifically, we can describe the final target shape as being like a rifle bullseye. There's a single center tile of the color, And then there's two tiles worth of background color going up down left and right from that single center tile. There's then a layer of colored tiles surrounding that cross-like shape, and four additional tiles in some of the exterior corners of that single layer. It's hard to describe in words what the shape actually is, but if you inspect the four objects closely and try to overlap them, then you'll see the missing tiles. The rest of the output grid is exactly the same, with the exception of these additional tiles of the corresponding colors that need to be added to complete the shape.
